          "body": "*Jesus wept* (11:35) is famously brief, and it does decisive work against any docetic or Stoic reading of the incarnation. The Lord of life weeps at a grave. But John pairs it with a stronger word twice (11:33, 38) — *embrimaomai*, the verb of snorting indignation. Jesus is not merely sad; He is angry at death itself, at the unbelief that surrounds Him, at the curse that puts His friend in a cave. B. B. Warfield's classic essay *On the Emotional Life of Our Lord* (1912) lingers here: Jesus enters grief without being mastered by it, and His grief is righteous wrath against the enemy He is about to defeat. He does not stand above the funeral; He stands in it — and against it."
